### species background   

#### general    
- largest snakes in Puerto Rico (1.8-2.7 m long)  
- most common in NW - karst landscapes  
- nocturnal, arboreal ([Reagan 1984](background/reagan_1984.pdf){target="_blank"})  
- hang from tail in front of cave openings to capture bats ([Rodriguez-Duran 1996](background/rodriguez-duran_1996.pdf){target="_blank"})  
- variety of habitats and prey ([Wiley 2003](background/wiley_2003.pdf){target="_blank"})  
- average homerange ~8.5 ha for both sexes ([Wunderle et al 2004](background/wunderle_etal_2004.pdf){target="_blank"})  
- little genetic structure among populations ([Puente-Rolon et al 2013](background/puente-rolon_etal_2013.pdf){target="_blank"})  
   
#### life history     
- mate in spring (beginning of wet season)  
- viviparous, ~20 young per clutch, range 13-30 ([Wiley 2003](background/wiley_2003.pdf){target="_blank"})    
- lifespan up to 20 years in captivity, unknown in wild  
- four-stage life cycle: young of the year (Y), juvenile (J), sub-adult (S), adult (A)   
$$
\left[\begin{array}
{rrr}
0 & 0 & F^{S} & F^{A} \\
T^{YJ} & S^J & 0 & 0 \\
0 & T^{JS} & S^S & 0 \\
0 & 0 & T^{SA} & S^A \\
\end{array}\right]
$$
  
#### threats  
- habitat loss (esp. after hurricanes)    
- historically harvested for oil  
- electrical wiring  
- road mortality  
- human persecution  
- food availabiilty (bat population collapse post-Maria)  
- diseases  
- collection for pet trade  
  
#### protection history   
- [listed Endangered 1970](https://ecos.fws.gov/ecp0/profile/speciesProfile?spcode=C00P#recovery){target="_blank"}   
- [Recovery Plan](background/recovery-plan.pdf){target="_blank"} approved 1986, no measurable targets set, recommended further surveys  
- [5-Year Review 2011](background/five-year-review-2011.pdf){target="_blank"} (another initiated 2016- not in ECOS)  


  
  
### available data  
- some demographic rates in literature  
- shapefiles  
- QGIS project - layers:  
  + `epicrates_inornatus_habitat.img` (available)  
  + `EpicratesInornatusHEX.shp` (missing)  
  + `lifezones83.shp` (missing)  
  + `pr_geodata-g03_legales_limites_lines_2015.kml` (missing)  
  + `tl_2017_us_county.shp` (found online)   
- from Holdridge life zones shapefile (`holdridge.shp`), two types on PR:  
  + zone 29 - subtropical moist forest (middle)  
  + zone 36 - tropical dry forest (east and west sides)  



